{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585372"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:10:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:10:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14961"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14961"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.04,0.8,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66424"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7649"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14961"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51875"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6738"},{"type":"tags","id":"7687"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8109"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22215"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66424"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents with a five-day history of fever, sore throat, and fatigue. On examination she has several enlarged, soft lymph nodes in her left posterior triangle of the neck. A lymph node biopsy is performed, showing large atypical lymphoid cells with prominent nucleoli and abundant cytoplasm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following viruses is most likely responsible for these histological changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenovirus","Coronavirus-19","Epstein-Barr virus","Paramyxovirus","Rotavirus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and histological findings occurr infectious mononucleosis caused by \u003Cem\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/em\u003E (EBV). The histological hallmark of \u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E infection is the presence of large atypical lymphocytes (immunoblasts) with abundant cytoplasm and prominent nucleoli, sometimes resembling Reed-Sternberg cells. These cells represent activated T lymphocytes responding to EBV-infected B cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenovirus\u003C/strong\u003E infection typically shows intranuclear inclusion bodies within respiratory epithelial cells rather than lymphoid proliferation. While it can cause pharyngitis, the histological changes are distinctly different from those seen in EBV infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronavirus-19\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects respiratory epithelium, showing diffuse alveolar damage with hyaline membrane formation in severe cases. It does not typically cause significant lymphoid proliferation or the characteristic immunoblastic changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotavirus\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the gastrointestinal tract, causing villous blunting and inflammatory changes in the intestinal mucosa. It would not cause the lymphoid proliferation or systemic symptoms seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParamyxovirus\u003C/strong\u003E infections (such as measles) can show multinucleated giant cells (Warthin-Finkeldey cells) but do not produce the immunoblastic proliferation characteristic of EBV infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of EBV infection can be confirmed by serological testing for viral capsid antigen (VCA) IgM and IgG antibodies, as well as flow cytometry showing CD8+ T-cell predominance. The combination of clinical features (fever, pharyngitis, lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly) and characteristic histological findings makes EBV the most likely causative agent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epstein-Barr virus causes characteristic Reed-Sternberg-like immunoblasts on histology.","Atypical lymphocytes with abundant cytoplasm and prominent nucleoli are characteristic of infectious mononucleosis.","Flow cytometry showing CD8+ T-cell predominance helps confirm EBV infection."],"references":["Yu H, Robertson ES. Epstein-Barr Virus History and Pathogenesis. Viruses. 2023 Mar 9;15(3):714. doi: 10.3390/v15030714. PMID: 36992423; PMCID: PMC10056551.","Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51875"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14961"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51875"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T08:52:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T08:52:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7649"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66424"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"